If Ruben Amorim is to be sacked, I think we have 3 options:
1. Carlos Queiroz
2. David Moyes
3. Ole Gunnar‚Ä®
We have to accept that we are a good team in the transition from defense to attack. The best form of this was implemented in Oleg Guo's first season, also during Ten Hag's era we could conclude in the transition game, which Ten Hag realized in his first season after the second defeat, and in fact the problem started when he decided to implement his philosophy in the team in the following seasons, which the club owners and fans did not have enough patience. What is happening now with Amorim. In fact, if we still win the game, it is on the counterattack or some situantions like free kicks.
the fact that he still insists on the 3-back format does not mean that he is exactly implementing his philosophy at Sporting at United (in fact he is trying but not succeeding). It seems that his insistence on playing with three defenders is only to continue to instill his sense of leadership in the team, apparently to prevent it from falling apart.

@sadegh_drg Adapting this United to Ruben Amorim's football philosophy or any other style with any other coach (except for regular defense and quick transitions from defense to attack) with no unity and lack of motivation in the team will be a very time-consuming and difficult process that fans and owners will not be able to tolerate for several years of frustration.
So with these interpretations, the best option is to return to a charismatic and professional manager with a history of being at United and of course a style of playing regular defense with quick counterattacks. (Quick and accurate transitions from defense to attack).
After creating motivation and unity in the team and also a belief in the championship, other styles can be planned. However, if a team like United achieves impressive championships in this style (transitional play), it can be the owner of its own style in a new form at the level of modern world football.
With Rashford's return, we have all the necessary players (the high speed of players like Rashford and Amad and even Dalot, the best playmaker in the world in free roaming Bruno, a physical finisher like Brian Mbeumu and ball-playing defenders like Yoro, Shaw, Licha and...)
Now I think the best option is Carlos Queiroz because he is disciplined and charismatic and has experience in building new generations of football in a team (like Iran) and most importantly he was Sir Alex's assistant.
And since Moyes and Ole were recently the team's coaches, it might not seem very logical to return to them.
